==Old English==
===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/'maɣa/}}

====Etymology====
From Germanic ''*magē-'', from Indo-European ''*mak-'' ‘bag, belly’. Cognate with Old Frisian ''maga'', Middle Dutch [[maghe]] (Dutch [[maag]]), Old High German [[mago]] (German [[Magen]]), Old Norse [[magi]] (Swedish [[mage#Swedish|mage]]). The IE root is also the source of Celtic ''*makno-'' (Welsh [[megin]] ‘bellows’), Slavic ''*mošьnā'' (Old Church Slavonic [[мошьна]], Russian [[мошна]] ‘pocket, bag’), Baltic ''*maka-'' (Lithuanian [[makas|mãkas]] ‘purse’).

====Noun====
'''maga''' {{m}}
# the [[stomach]] of an animal or person

====Descendents====
*English [[maw]]

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/'ma:ɣa/}}

====Noun form====
'''māga'''
# genitive plural of [[mæg|mǣġ]]


